<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · Double wall oven issues</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Lower cavity fails 3 to 4 years before the upper. Configuration matters at diagnostic.</h2>

    <p>Double wall ovens (two cavities stacked vertically in a single 27-inch or 30-inch unit) are the largest premium kitchen segment in Los Angeles, Orange, and Ventura counties. Brand pool: GE Profile JT3000/JT5000, KitchenAid Architect KODE/KEDC, Whirlpool WOD/WOC, Wolf E-series DO30/DO30CM, Miele PureLine H 7440/7660 30-inch double, Thermador Professional ME302/ME272, GE Monogram ZET.</p>

    <p>The dominant service pattern across all of these brands: <strong>lower cavity components fail 3 to 4 years before equivalent upper cavity components.</strong> The "lower not heating, upper works fine" call is our #1 double-oven service request, by a wide margin.</p>

    <p>Why the lower fails first:</p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Cabinet heat trap.</strong> Heat rises during cooking; lower cavity sits in elevated ambient between cycles, components accumulate thermal stress at higher rates than upper.</li>
      <li><strong>Daily use frequency.</strong> Lower cavity used 60 to 70% of cooking sessions in typical household. Upper used for larger occasions.</li>
      <li><strong>Door cycling.</strong> Lower door opened more times, hinges and switches cycle more.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>This page covers the configuration education we deliver at every $89 double-oven diagnostic, plus the manufacturer warranty submission help we provide on units still in coverage.</p>

    <p><strong>$89 residential diagnostic, waived with repair.</strong> Or used as written-report-only for manufacturer warranty submission. BHGS Licensed #A49573 and EPA 608 Universal certified (#1346255700410). 90-day warranty. Same-day across LA, OC, Ventura. Sister sub-services: <a href="/services/wall-oven-repair/not-heating/">not heating</a>, <a href="/services/wall-oven-repair/door-issues/">door issues</a>, <a href="/services/wall-oven-repair/control-board-failure/">control board failure</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 MANUFACTURER WARRANTY (Roman tweak #3) -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Manufacturer warranty submission help</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">If your unit's still in coverage, we'd rather you use it.</h2>

    <p>Premium double wall ovens carry meaningful manufacturer warranty windows. When your unit fails inside that window, the right path is the manufacturer's authorized service network, not an out-of-pocket repair. We're honest about it.</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>Wolf E-series.</strong> 2-year full warranty on parts and labor, standard. Plus an additional 5-year limited on specific components (sealed system, certain electronic boards) depending on model and year. Sub-Zero Group authorized service handles claims.</li>
      <li><strong>Miele PureLine.</strong> 1-year full standard, plus extended programs (Miele Reassurance) on M Touch and M Pro that extend coverage on motor, control, and certain assemblies. Miele USA dispatches authorized service.</li>
      <li><strong>Thermador Professional and Gaggenau.</strong> 1-year full standard. BSH Group authorized service handles claims.</li>
      <li><strong>GE Profile and Monogram.</strong> 1-year full standard, plus optional GE-extended (Asurion) programs on units sold with extended coverage. GE Appliances dispatches authorized service.</li>
      <li><strong>KitchenAid Architect, Whirlpool, JennAir.</strong> 1-year full standard. Whirlpool family authorized service network.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>How our warranty submission help works:</p>

    <ol class="ordered-list">
      <li><strong>$89 diagnostic visit.</strong> We come out, identify the failed component, document the unit (model, serial, age confirmation), photograph the failure mode, capture the fault code.</li>
      <li><strong>Written diagnostic report, emailed same day.</strong> Includes model and serial verification, age, fault code, identified failed component, our BHGS license number for credibility with the manufacturer's claims desk.</li>
      <li><strong>You forward the report to manufacturer authorized service.</strong> Sub-Zero Group, Miele USA, BSH (Thermador, Gaggenau, Bosch), GE Appliances, or Whirlpool authorized network. Most accept independent licensed diagnostic reports for triage and accelerate scheduling.</li>
      <li><strong>Manufacturer dispatches their authorized tech.</strong> You pay nothing for the repair (within warranty terms). The $89 you paid us is buying the diagnostic and the documentation, not the repair.</li>
      <li><strong>Optional fallback.</strong> If the manufacturer's authorized tech can't schedule within your timeline (sometimes 2 to 4 weeks at peak season), you can authorize us to repair it ourselves. The $89 waives into the repair line. We'd still recommend pursuing reimbursement from the manufacturer with our report attached.</li>
    </ol>

    <p>This is a deliberately customer-first model. We make less money when your unit's in warranty than when it isn't. We do it because the alternative — quietly repairing a unit that the manufacturer would have repaired free — is the kind of thing that erodes trust in this industry.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 LOWER FAILS FIRST -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · "Lower not heating, upper works fine" diagnostic</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Three usual causes, in order of frequency.</h2>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>1. Lower bake element burnout</h3>
      <p>Heating element at the bottom of the lower cavity, looped tube. Over years of cycling and self-clean exposure, the resistance wire inside breaks. Visible symptom: black or burned spot on the element. Resistance check (19 to 30 ohms healthy) confirms. Lower bake element replacement runs $180 to $340 mid-tier, $440 to $780 pro-tier. Lower fails first by 3 to 4 years on doubles.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>2. Lower cavity RTD temperature sensor drift</h3>
      <p>Resistance temperature detector measures cavity temperature. Healthy reading approximately 1,080 ohms at room temperature. When it drifts (200+ ohms off), the control board reads incorrect temperature and either underheats (slow cook) or shuts off as a safety measure. $120 to $260 part, in-line labor.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="cause-block">
      <h3>3. Lower cavity bake relay (control board)</h3>
      <p>The relay on the main control board that switches power to the lower bake element. When this single relay fails, the lower won't heat even though the element and sensor are healthy. Mid-tier solution: full board replacement $440 to $720 (cap-level relay swap not standard practice). Pro-tier integrated boards $1,200 to $2,400 plus authorized programming. We confirm the relay is the failure point at diagnostic by bench-testing the element and sensor independently.</p>
    </div>

    <p>Pattern recognition: when the lower fails at year 9, the upper is typically 60 to 80% along the same wear curve. We always offer paired replacement (lower failed component plus upper proactive equivalent) as an option. Adding the upper part costs $80 to $160 parts, no extra labor. Saves a full second service call within 12 to 24 months on most units.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 BRAND CONFIGURATIONS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Brand configuration notes</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What's distinct on each double-oven family.</h2>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>GE Profile JT3000 and JT5000.</strong> Mid-tier double-oven workhorse, common in mid-2000s through 2010s LA homes. Lower-fails-first pattern strongest here. Bake element and RTD sensor parts inexpensive and well-stocked.</li>
      <li><strong>KitchenAid Architect KODE and KEDC.</strong> Whirlpool family premium tier. KODE is electric-only, KEDC adds convection. Same lower-first pattern; F-codes mirror Whirlpool architecture. UI board failures common 2014-2019 generation (KitchenAid F2E2).</li>
      <li><strong>Whirlpool WOD and WOC.</strong> Mid-tier mass-market. WOC is convection variant. Lower-first pattern. Parts pipeline very well-stocked, fast turnaround.</li>
      <li><strong>Wolf E-series DO30 and DO30CM.</strong> Pro-tier residential, dual-convection in DO30CM. 2-year manufacturer warranty standard. Lower-first pattern still applies but slower wear curve given premium component sourcing. Sub-Zero Group authorized.</li>
      <li><strong>Miele PureLine H 7440 and H 7660 30-inch double.</strong> Pro-tier German. M Touch UI on PureLine generation. Authorized parts pipeline 5 to 10 days. Miele Reassurance extended programs common.</li>
      <li><strong>Thermador Professional ME302 and ME272.</strong> Pro-tier with Star burner heritage on cooktop pairing. ME302 single, ME272 double. BSH authorized.</li>
      <li><strong>GE Monogram ZET.</strong> Premium GE built-in. Distinct hardware platform from GE Profile despite shared parent. Authorized GE Appliances service.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 PRICING -->
<section class="section">
